<h2 id="relations">Relations</h2>

<h3 id="recalling-relation">Recalling <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finitary_relation">Relation</a></h3>

<p>from FCT/TAPL/Wikiâ€¦</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>a possible connection between the components of a k-tuple.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I have been long confused with <em>Unary Relations vs. Binary Relation on the Same Set (homogeneous relation)</em>
I thought they were sameâ€¦but turns out they are totally different!</p>

<h4 id="unary1-place-relation-is-predicate-or-property">Unary/1-place relation is <strong>Predicate</strong> or <strong>Property</strong>!</h4>

<p>Either defined via set <code class="highlighter-rouge">X âŠ† P</code> or <code class="highlighter-rouge">x âˆˆ P</code>,
or defined via function <code class="highlighter-rouge">P : X -&gt; Bool</code> or <code class="highlighter-rouge">P : X -&gt; {âŠ¥, âŠ¤}</code>.
(usually used in Math. Logic)</p>

<p>Property = Indicator Fn = characteristic Fn = Boolean Predicate Fn = Predicate</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Property_(mathematics)">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Property_(mathematics)</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicator_function">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicator_function</a></li>
</ul>

<h4 id="binary-relation2-place-relation"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_relation">Binary Relation/2-place relation</a></h4>

<p>Defined via two sets : <code class="highlighter-rouge">R âŠ† X Ã— Y</code> or <code class="highlighter-rouge">x, y âˆˆ R</code> or <code class="highlighter-rouge">xRy</code>.  (where <code class="highlighter-rouge">x âˆˆ X, y âˆˆ Y</code>.)
or via function <code class="highlighter-rouge">R: X Ã— Y -&gt; Bool</code>.</p>

<h5 id="homogeneous-relation-åŒç±»çš„å…³ç³»"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_relation#Homogeneous_relation">Homogeneous Relation åŒç±»ï¼ˆçš„ï¼‰å…³ç³»</a></h5>

<p>Specifically! when <code class="highlighter-rouge">X = Y</code>, is called a <em>homogeneous relation</em>:</p>

<p>Noticed that we are still concerning relations of <strong>2 elements</strong>!!, but they are from the same Set!
(while 1-place relation concerning only 1 element.)</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><table class="rouge-table"><tbody><tr><td class="rouge-gutter gl"><pre class="lineno">1
2
</pre></td><td class="rouge-code"><pre>R âŠ† X Ã— X
xRy where x âˆˆ X, y âˆˆ X
</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></code></pre></div></div>

<p>itâ€™s written/spoken <em>Binary</em> relation <strong>on/over</strong> Set <code class="highlighter-rouge">X</code>. 
Properties e.g. <em>reflexive, symmetric, transitive</em>, are all properties of â€œHomogeneous Relationâ€!</p>

<h3 id="back-to-coq">Back to Coq</h3>

<p>â€œrelationâ€ is a general idea. but in Coq standard lib it means â€œbinary relation on <em>a</em> set Xâ€</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>Coq <code class="highlighter-rouge">identifier</code> relation will always refer to a binary relation between some set and itself.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>itâ€™s defined as <em>a family of Prop parameterized by two elements of <code class="highlighter-rouge">X</code></em>:</p>

